Number one - there is nothing called &quot;constant variables&quot;. The correct terminology is &quot;constants&quot;.

The reason why the properties of the object you declared as a constant can be changed is that the object is referenced.


    var i = 200;
    const c = 300;
    const o = {foo: &quot;bar&quot;}

Now, in the above example,

The symbol `i` is understandably a variable which has the value of 200.

The symbol `c` is a constant whose value is fixed to 300.

The symbol `o` is a constant which refers to an object. The value of `o` **is a memory address** which points to an object. What cannot be changed is this memory address, not what is in the address itself.

&lt;!-- begin snippet: js hide: false console: true babel: false --&gt;

&lt;!-- language: lang-js --&gt;

    const o = {foo: &quot;bar&quot;};


    o.bar = &quot;foo&quot;;   //The object properties, whats in the memory location the constant points to, can be changed
    console.log(o);


    try {
       o = {bar: &quot;foo&quot;}       
       console.log(&#39;I changed the value of a constant&#39;)
    }
    catch(e) {
        console.log(&#39;I cannot change the value of a constant. But whatever in the memory where the value is pointing to&#39;)
    }

&lt;!-- end snippet --&gt;

